This song carries so much emotional weight for me - in 2017 at the age of 19 I went into Cardiac arrest and almost died. When I woke up i was in the hospital for a month and during this time i had to learn to read and write again due to oxygen loss in my brain and a seizure I had underwent because of the Arrest. This song was one of the first things I listened to after all of that in the fall/winter of 2017, This actually brings a tear to my eye and makes me heavy with nostalgia. Sometimes I want to go back but I'm proud of how far I've come. I will always love this song and these two artists for what they represented in my life at that time and even up to this moment. I overheard my roommate play this riff on his guitar 2-3 times back in 2018 in his room and never heard it again till now. Being that my roommate and I weren't close I never asked him while he was playing what the song was called and assumed there was a possibility he made it himself and was really talented. Towards the end of our time living together I remembered to ask him what the song was he was playing and tried humming it back to him but he couldn't make out what I was trying to hum. Anyways its just cool to think that the song he played stood out so much and then to finally find it via Instagram combined with SoundHound and seeing it has over 400 million views is awesome. Kinda cool that people can somewhat universally agree on what good music sounds like.

This song was presented to me by the guy I liked back in 2018. To this day, I don't really know what happened. I guess he lost interest and started treating me poorly and I got tired of suffering and begging for attention and walked away. Sometimes he comes to mind and it hurts a bit, not because I still want him, but because of all the promises of what could've been. When I am in a higher state of mind I get to see that it could have only been what it was. The way things happened was the only possible way. I needed that to grow. I needed to look at myself in the mirror and know that I have my back, even if he rejects me, even if the whole entire world rejects me â€” which I actually felt like sometimes. This song reminds me of him because he showed it to me, but it doesn't hurt when I listen to it. It's peaceful. And this is how I want to feel. I don't want to be with that guy anymore, but I want this hurt gone. I want to like someone else without ever having to compare them to him. And I'll get there. And when I do, I know it'll be like tadow. Just felt like writing.

THIS is the proper way to use loop pedals. I can't tell you how boring a song can get when musicians rely on looping, but I can tell you that definitely isn't happening here. FKJ & Masego start this piece off with what felt like a jam session, but eventually turned into an artfully composed, well structured song. I was worried in the beginning that there would be no progression to this song. Using loops can make a piece easily turn monotonous, but these guys knew how to keep it moving, almost giving the song purpose. They took a few solid minutes to really establish the piece, and in my honest opinion, that was too long. The structure could have been improved if the song was established in half that time, and then advances were made from there. You do need time to set up the beat and feel of the song, but you need to be careful not to bore your listeners. HOWEVER, if this were titled a jam session, I would be in total awe. This first half of the piece felt like it had no deliberate reason to exist or no purpose. Though it was quite beautiful, it wasn't going anywhere - like a straight line that has fun accidentals, but isn't pointing to anything worthwhile.  HOWEVER (AGAIN), this piece really changed my mind around the six-minute mark. It took them a while, but we finally got somewhere substantial! The lyrics, the melody, and everything in between finally had some substance! I mean just listen to the last 20 seconds of keyboard playing - almost ethereal. The lyrics also picked up around the same time, as well. I felt like he was finally saying something meaningful. All in all, this is an incredible song performed by clearly, insanely talented people. As much as I complained about the first 6 minutes being much longer than they should have been, after hearing the end really come together, I can overlook the slow pace of the song. Definitely a thumbs up!
